5. SAFETY, SECURITY, AND RELIABILITY

5.1 Safety Architecture

Multi-Layered Safety Approach:

1. Functional Safety (ISO 26262 ASIL-D):
   · Hardware redundancy for critical components
   · Diverse software implementations for key algorithms
   · Comprehensive fault detection and response
2. SOTIF - Safety of the Intended Functionality (ISO 21448):
   · Extensive testing for edge cases
   · Continual validation in real-world conditions
   · Transparency in system limitations
3. Expected Functional Safety:
   · Systems perform as expected under all conditions
   · Clear communication of system capabilities to users
   · Graceful degradation under system limitations
4. Operational Safety:
   · Safe interaction with human drivers and pedestrians
   · Predictable behavior in complex environments
   · Clear external communication of vehicle intentions

Safety Mechanisms:

· Triple Modular Redundancy: Critical sensors and compute
· Watchdog Timers: Monitor system health and responsiveness
· Safe States: Multiple defined safe states for different failure modes
· Fallback Levels: Graduated reduction in capability rather than complete failure

5.2 Security Architecture

Defense-in-Depth Security:

1. Physical Security:
   · Tamper-resistant hardware
   · Secure boot with hardware roots of trust
   · Physical attack detection and response
2. Network Security:
   · Post-quantum cryptography for all external communication
   · Network segmentation and micro-segmentation
   · Continuous traffic monitoring for anomalies
3. Application Security:
   · Secure coding practices throughout development
   · Regular security testing and penetration testing
   · Secure update mechanisms with cryptographic verification
4. Data Security:
   · Encryption of data at rest and in transit
   · Privacy-preserving data processing
   · User control over data sharing

Quantum-Resistant Security Timeline:

· 2024-2026: Hybrid classical-PQC implementations
· 2027-2029: Full PQC migration for all external interfaces
· 2030+: Quantum key distribution for highest security needs

5.3 Reliability Engineering

Reliability Targets:

· System Availability: 99.999% (5 nines)
· Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF): >50,000 hours
· Mean Time To Repair (MTTR): <1 hour for critical functions
· Data Integrity: 99.999999% (8 nines)

Reliability Mechanisms:

· Predictive Maintenance: AI predicts component failures before they occur
· Health Monitoring: Continuous monitoring of all system components
· Degraded Mode Operation: Continued operation with reduced capability
· Remote Diagnostics: Over-the-air diagnosis and repair guidance

